\begin_layout Subsubsection
Buyer's initial period offer with unique threshhold
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At time 0, the buyer knows better information will arrive at time 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and must decide how aggressive to be in inducing conservation today.
 If the buyer makes a large offer today, the parcel is likely to conserve,
 but the buyer risks both paying for non-additional conservation and conserving
 land that provides conservation benefits below the cost.
 On the other hand, if the buyer makes no offer today, any opportunity to
 alter landowner development decisions is lost since all land with 
\begin_inset Formula $\priv>0$
\end_inset

 will be developed immediately.
 The buyer must balance these concerns in deciding how aggressive to be
 with payments today.
 When there is a unique threshhold as described in the previous section,
 the buyer knows that the landowner will develop if 
\begin_inset Formula $\priv>\temp$
\end_inset

 and will conserve otherwise, implying that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ubPriv=\temp$
\end_inset

.
 This means that the buyer's full payoff is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\payFull\left(\temp\right)=\intop_{-\infty}^{\temp}\left(\mu_{\env|\priv}\left(\priv\right)-\temp\right)f_{\priv}\left(\priv\right)dp+\delta\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\regPay^{*}\left(\se,\temp\right)f_{\se}\left(\se\right)d\se.\label{eq:firstPeriodObjFunc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As shown in the appendix, this can be simplified to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{\priv}\left(\temp\right)\left(\meanE-\temp\right)-\sigma_{\env}\sigP\rhoEP f_{\priv}\left(\temp\right)+\delta\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\regPay^{*}\left(\se,\temp\right)^{*}\left(\se,\temp\right)f_{\se}\left(\se\right)d\se.
\]

\end_inset

The first-order condition for an interior solution is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{\priv}\left(\temp\right)\left(\meanE-\temp+\frac{\sigE}{\sigP}\rhoEP\left(\temp-\meanP\right)\right)+\delta\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{\partial\regPay^{*}}{\partial\ubPriv}\left(\se,\temp\right)f_{\se}\left(\se\right)d\se=F_{p}\left(\temp\right)
\]

\end_inset

This condition mirrors (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:p2FOC"

\end_inset

) in that the marginal cost of increasing the offer is the probability it
 will be accepted.
 The first term of the marginal benefit of increasing the offer is the same
 as in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:p2FOC"

\end_inset

): the expected gain in the initial period conditional on the parcel's decision
 being changed times the probability of its choice is changed.
 The new element is the benefit of increasing the probability that the parcel
 will be undeveloped at time 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 when the signal is observed.
 By the envelope theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\regPay^{*}}{\partial\ubPriv}\left(\se,\temp\right)=0$
\end_inset

 if the upper bound is not binding in the second period problem and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\regPay^{*}}{\partial\ubPriv}\left(\se,\temp\right)=\drpf\left(\ubPriv,\se\right)>0$
\end_inset

 when the upper bound is binding.
 Therefore, the new term is necessarily non-negative and considering the
 second period will (weakly) lead to an increase in initial offers.
 The key question is how much it will increase offers and how large the
 gains will be.
 To answer these questions, I turn to numerical simulation since the model
 has no analytical solution.
\end_layout

